05507nam a22008175i 9780812296761DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122967617 a10.9783/97808122967612doi  a(DE-B1597)531775  a(OCoLC)1143793406  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDA205b.B35 2020eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a942.030722231 aBainton, Henry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHistory and the Written Word :bDocuments, Literacy, and Language in the Age of the Angevins /cHenry Bainton. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b2 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Orthography and Translations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Defining Documents -- tChapter 2. Documentary Quotation -- tChapter 3. Literate Sociability -- tChapter 4. Literate Performances and Literate Government -- tChapter 5. Literate Languages -- tAfterword -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aComing upon the text of a document such as a charter or a letter inserted into the fabric of a medieval chronicle and "ed in full or at length, modern readers might well assume that the chronicler is simply doing what good historians have always done—that is, citing his source as evidence. Such documentary insertions are not ubiquitous in medieval historiography, however, and are in fact particularly characteristic of the history-writing produced by the Angevins in England and Northern France in the later twelfth century.In History and the Written Word, Henry Bainton puts these documentary gestures center stage in an attempt to understand what the chroniclers were doing historiographically, socially, and culturally when they transcribed a document into a work of history. Where earlier scholars who have looked at the phenomenon have explained this increased use of documents by considering the growing bureaucratic state and an increasing historiographical concern for documentary evidence, Bainton seeks to resituate these histories, together with their authors and users, within literate but sub-state networks of political power. Proposing a new category he designates "literate lordship" to describe the form of power with which documentary history-writing was especially concerned, he shows how important the vernacular was in recording the social lives of these literate lords and how they found it a particularly appropriate medium through which to record their roles in history.Drawing on the perspectives of modern and medieval narratology, medieval multilingualism, and cultural memory, History and the Written Word argues that members of an administrative elite demonstrated their mastery of the rules of literate political behavior by producing and consuming history-writing and its documents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aLiteracyzEnglandxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook